mist-go is a shared Go library — the foundation that [matchspec](/matchspec/), [infermux](/infermux/), [schemaflux](/schemaflux/), and [tokentrace](/tokentrace/) are all built on. Rather than each tool reimplementing transport handling, configuration loading, circuit breaking, and observability independently, those concerns live in mist-go and are shared across the entire stack. The result is a consistent programming model: code written against mist-go works the same way in every MIST tool, and every MIST tool exposes the same operational surface.

The library is organized around a protocol-first design principle. Every message that crosses a tool boundary — an inference request from matchspec to infermux, a trace span from infermux to tokentrace, a schema definition from schemaflux to downstream consumers — uses the same `protocol.Message` envelope. The envelope carries a version, a random message ID, a source identifier, a type string, a nanosecond timestamp, a JSON payload, and an optional CRC32 checksum. This uniformity means tools can route, log, and audit messages without knowing their contents, and the `transport` package can carry any message over any wire without modification.

The transport abstraction is deliberately thin. The `Transport` interface has three methods: `Send`, `Receive`, and `Close`. `transport.Dial` selects an implementation based on a URL scheme: `http://` for network services, `file://` for batch pipelines, `stdio://` for Unix pipes, and `chan://` for in-process testing. Swapping HTTP for file or stdio requires changing one line in your configuration — the application code that calls `Send` and `Receive` does not change. This is particularly valuable for testing: a test that uses `transport.NewChannelPair` instead of `transport.NewHTTP` gets full coverage of application logic with no network required.

Zero external dependencies is a non-negotiable constraint for infrastructure code. A library that pulls in third-party packages creates supply chain exposure, makes vendoring harder, and creates version conflict risk when the library is embedded in other projects. mist-go implements everything it needs from the Go standard library: a TOML parser, a structured logger wrapper (built on `log/slog`, standard since Go 1.21), distributed tracing, metrics with lock-free atomic operations, exponential backoff with jitter, circuit breaking with configurable thresholds, and W3C Trace Context propagation over HTTP. The `go.mod` lists nothing beyond the module declaration and the Go version requirement.
